Introduction

The MIMIC-III (Medical Information Mart for Intensive Care III) is a database containing deidentified health-related data for over 40,000 patients staying in critical care units of Beth Israel Denaconess Medical Center between 2001 and 2012. The database consists of forty different tables pertaining to hospital admissions, patient demographics, patient diagnosis, prescriptions, etc. The following analysis seeks to predict the mortality rate of patients diagnosed with pneumonia who were admitted to the medical intensive care unit (MICU) thirty days after discharge.

Data Preparation

The MIMIC-III data is accessed by connecting to the PostgresSQL database. A cohort of patients directly admitted into MICU is extracted from the transfer table which contains information about the physical location of patients throughout their hospital stay. The d_icd_diagnoses table labels all diagnoses according to the Dictionary of International Classification of Diseases, 9th Revision (ICD-9 Codes). From this table, all ICD-9 codes related to pneumonia are stored and matched to patients’ ICD-9 codes in the diagnoses_icd table, so that only patients diagnosed with pnuemonia remain. Pneumonia may not be listed as the principal diagnosis as explained in the documentation for the patients table. The seq_num field is a priority ranking for the diagnoses generated at the end of stay. To focus on patients for whom pneumonia was central to their hospitalization, records with pnuemonia in any of the first five diagnosis positions, according to seq_num, is kept. The dataset containing only patients from MICU is joined with the dataset containing only pneumonia patients to obtain a cohort restricted to pneumonia patients who were directly admitted into the MICU (cohort_admissions)

A new logical variable (principal_dx) is added to cohort_admissions indicating whether pneumonia is the first diagnosis. A new variable (drg_severity) is also added classifying the severity of patients’ ailments from 1-4 with 1 as least severe and 4 as most severe. This information is obtained from the drgcodes table, containing severity and mortality indicators for DRG codes from the All Payers Registry (APR). From the admissions table, admission time (admittime), discharge time (dischtime), date of birth (dob), date of death (dod), and age at admission (age) are joined to cohort_admissions for patients who did not die in hospital and are younger than 90 years old. The dataset is restricted because patients older than 90 have artifically inflated ages to keep the data de-identifiable. Lastly, gender and ethnicity is joined to cohort_admissions from the patients table.

  left_join(
    select(tbl(con, "admissions"),

Add age (at admission) variable into the table; remove patients older than 90 yrs from the analysis

cohort_admissions %>%
  mutate(tt_death = DATE_PART("day", dod - dischtime)) %>%
  mutate(mortality = tt_death <= 30) %>%
  mutate(age = date_part("year", admittime) - date_part("year", dob)) %>%
  filter(age < 90) %>%
  mutate(age = age - ifelse(
    date_part("month", admittime) < date_part("month", dob) |
      (
        date_part("month", admittime) == date_part("month", dob) &
          date_part("day", admittime) < date_part("day", dob)
      ),
    1,
    0
  )) %>%
  select(-admittime, -dischtime, -dob, -dod, -tt_death) %>%
  select(subject_id, hadm_id, age, mortality, everything()) %>%
  print() -> cohort_admissions

Resolve some diversity and inconsistency in the ethnicity field

unknown_ethnicity <- c(
  "OTHER",
  "UNABLE TO OBTAIN",
  "UNKNOWN/NOT SPECIFIED",
  "MULTI RACE ETHNICITY",
  "PATIENT DECLINED TO ANSWER",
  "UNKNOWN"
)

cohort_subjects %>%
  collect() %>%
  mutate(ethnic_group = case_when(
    str_detect(ethnicity, "^ASIAN") ~ "ASIAN",
    str_detect(ethnicity, "^BLACK") ~ "BLACK",
    str_detect(ethnicity, "^HISPANIC") ~ "HISPANIC",
    str_detect(ethnicity, "^WHITE") ~ "WHITE",
    ethnicity %in% unknown_ethnicity ~ NA_character_,
    TRUE ~ NA_character_
  )) %>%
  select(subject_id, gender, ethnic_group) %>%
  print() -> cohort_subjects

Some patients are coded as belonging to more than one ethnic group. To resolve these inconsistencies, define a helper function to pick the modal value from a vector of values in R, which can be used by the summarize() function to choose one ethnic group for each patient

most <- function(x) {
  if (all(is.na(x))) return(NA_character_)
  y <- table(x, useNA = "no")
  if (length(which(y == max(y))) > 1) return(NA_character_)
  return(names(y)[which.max(y)])
}

cohort_subjects %>%
  group_by(subject_id) %>%
  summarize(ethnic_group = most(ethnic_group)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(ethnic_group = ifelse(is.na(ethnic_group), "UNKNOWN", ethnic_group)) %>%
  print() -> cohort_ethnic_groups

Analysis

A predictive model for the 30-day mortality rate of patients admitted into MICU is developed using logistic regression and neural network. Their predictive performance is compared using root mean squared error (RMSE) and summarized via graphs.

1. Logistic Regression

Before running a logistic regression, the ICD-9 Codes are recoded as an indicator variable with 1 representing the ICD-9 code for the patient is in the top five most common types of pneumonia. Additionally, all character variables are converted into factors. The cohort_admissions data is split into a training and test set with 75% of the observations in the training set. A logistic regression is performed on the training set with age, drug severity, ICD-9 code, principal drug, gender, and ethnic group as the covariates. A root mean squared error (RMSE) is calculated to measure performance.

final_cohort1 <- final_cohort

# Recode icd9_code
top_5 <- c("486", "48241", "4829", "4821", "99731")
final_cohort1$icd9_code <- ifelse(final_cohort1$icd9_code %in% top_5, 
                                  TRUE, FALSE)

# 75% of the sample size
smp_size <- floor(0.75 * nrow(final_cohort))

# Make all character variables into factors
columns <- c("drg_severity", "gender", "ethnic_group")

final_cohort1[,columns] <- lapply(final_cohort1[, columns], as.factor)

# Set the seed to make partition reproducible
set.seed(12345)

# Create a training and testing set
train_ind <- sample(seq_len(nrow(final_cohort1)), size = smp_size)
train <- final_cohort1[train_ind, ]
test <- final_cohort1[-train_ind, ]

# Build the logistic regression model
logit <- glm(mortality ~ age + drg_severity + icd9_code + principal_dx + 
               gender + ethnic_group, data = train, family = binomial)

summary(logit)

mortality_hat <- predict(logit, test, type = "response")

sq_diff <- (test$mortality - mortality_hat)^2
root_mse <- sqrt(mean(sq_diff, na.rm = TRUE))

2. Neural Network

Before running a neural network, all categorical variables are converted to dummy variables, and subject_id and hadm_id are removed from the model since they are unique to each patient and have no association to mortality rate. Additionally, the neural network cannot be performed on variables with missing data, so all observations containing a missing value are removed from the dataset. This reduces the data to 2,183 patients. The data is further split up into a training and test set with 1,637 and 546 patients respectively. The neural network is performed on the training set and predicted on the test set. A RMSE is calculated to measure performance.

# Install Neural Network Package if necessary
if("neuralnet" %in% rownames(installed.packages()) == FALSE) {install.packages("neuralnet")}
library(neuralnet)
## 
## Attaching package: 'neuralnet'
## The following object is masked from 'package:dplyr':
## 
##     compute
# Convert all categorical variables to dummy variables 
final_cohort2 <- final_cohort1 %>%
  mutate(mortality = ifelse(mortality==TRUE, 1, 0),
         principal_dx = ifelse(principal_dx==TRUE, 1, 0),
         icd9_code = ifelse(icd9_code==TRUE, 1, 0),
         gender = ifelse(gender=="M", 1, 0),
         drg_sev1 = ifelse(drg_severity==1, 1, 0),
         drg_sev2 = ifelse(drg_severity==2, 1, 0),
         drg_sev3 = ifelse(drg_severity==3, 1, 0),
         drg_sev4 = ifelse(drg_severity==4, 1, 0),
         white = ifelse(ethnic_group=="WHITE", 1, 0),
         asian = ifelse(ethnic_group=="ASIAN", 1, 0),
         black = ifelse(ethnic_group=="BLACK", 1, 0),
         hispanic = ifelse(ethnic_group=="HISPANIC", 1, 0),
         other = ifelse(ethnic_group=="OTHER", 1, 0),
         age = scale(age)) %>% 
  select(-c("subject_id", "hadm_id", "drg_severity", "ethnic_group")) %>% 
  select("mortality", everything())

# Remove NA's from mortality and create training set
final_tt <- na.omit(final_cohort2)
tt_size <- floor(0.75 * nrow(final_tt))
tt_ind <- sample(seq_len(nrow(final_tt)), size = tt_size)

ttrain <- final_tt[tt_ind, ]
x_train <- ttrain %>% select(-mortality)

# Create testing set
ttest <- final_tt[-tt_ind, ]
x_test <- ttest %>% select(-mortality)


# Run the Neural Network
set.seed(12345)
NN <- neuralnet(mortality ~ age + icd9_code + gender + drg_sev1 + drg_sev2 +
                 drg_sev3 + drg_sev4 + white + asian + black + hispanic + other, 
               ttrain, hidden = 3 , linear.output = T )

# Plot neural network
plot(NN, rep = "best")

# Prediction 
predict_testNN <- compute(NN, x_test)
predict_testNN <- (predict_testNN$net.result * 
                    (max(final_tt$mortality) - min(final_tt$mortality))) + 
  min(final_tt$mortality)

# Calculate RMSE
RMSE.NN <- (sum((ttest$mortality - predict_testNN)^2) / nrow(ttest)) ^ 0.5
paste("Root MSE:", round(RMSE.NN, 4), sep = " ")
## [1] "Root MSE: 0.4103"

Conclusion

From the running the two models, it appears that the logistic regression is better at predicting 30-day mortality rate for patients with pneumonia who were admitted to the MICU. From the logistic regression, it appears that age and a drug severity of 4 (highest) are significant factors in predicting 30-day mortality rate. The logistic regression resulted in a RMSE of 0.396 compared to a RMSE of 0.410 for the neural network. Both models result in a relatively low RMSE; the closer the RMSE is to zero, the better the predictive model. However, a factor in contributing to a lower RMSE for neural network could be that nearly half of the observations are removed due to missing data. Future analysis includes using a better method than omission to deal with missing data.
